<table width="100%" align="center" cellpadding="1"  cellspacing="1" border="1" bordercolor="#660000" bgcolor="#000000" class="nav">
	<tr>
		<td background="../../images/cellpic1.gif" align="center" class="title">Killing As An Organized Sport</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td bgcolor="#000000" bordercolor="#000000" class="maintext">
<h1><div align="center">The Scribery</div></h1>
<h3 align="center">The Arrival</h3>

  <p><font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="-1">Sitting upon a large 
    grey stone, an old man looked down at the mass of children, who has gathered 
    around him, who had come to hear one of his tales. A long, knotted grey beard 
    hung down passed the wrinkled skin of his throat, the only hair that could 
    be seen on his head. The old man's eyes could barely be seen behind the thick 
    lenses of his glasses, glasses which lay in the shadows cast by the wide brimmed 
    hat he was wearing. </font></p>
  <p><font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="-1">With the slowest and 
    most subtle of movements, the old man's frail hands opened the cover of a 
    weathered tome. The children murmured amongst themselves, but one glance from 
    the old man silenced them. As the old man began to tell his story, a story 
    of woe and sorrow, of pain and anguish, the sky above them began to cloud 
    over with dark clouds and the ominous sound of thunder could be heard off 
    in the distance.</font></p>
  <p><font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="-1"> With a storm brewing 
    around them, the old man continued his tale, and the children listened with 
    rapt attention, and more than a couple of them bit their lips as shivers were 
    sent through their bodies from the old man's words. Nodding to himself before 
    continuing, the old man recounted the scariest story he could think of while 
    beads of sweat began to appear on his leathery brow. For, this story brought 
    fear to all, the old, the young, the strong, the weak. </font></p>
  <p><font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="-1">All feared the horrid 
    tales of KAAOS. </font></p>
  <p><font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="-1">The old man paused in 
    mid verse, leaving the children to their own thoughts as he remembered the 
    tales he, himself, had heard when he was a child. Many thought that these 
    stories were just used to put a scare in children, but the old man knew better. 
    His fingers unconsciously let go of the tome he had held in his hands and 
    they moved to his cheek, tracing a long purple scar which had been concealed 
    in shadow. </font></p>
  <p><font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="-1">As his fingers touched 
    the scar, he heard his father's words echoing in his head and in front of 
    him, he no longer saw the massed children, but instead he saw himself sitting 
    before his father as his father recounted this same tale. He listened now 
    as if he had never heard this story before. </font></p>
  <p><font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="-1">The old man listened 
    to his father telling of how the forces which he called KAAOS had once existed 
    in some far off realm. KAAOS, as they called themselves, was a band of the 
    most twisted and warped that any had ever come in contact with, their power 
    being so strong that they were seen as gods and worshipped as them, as well, 
    his father explained to him in the flashback. When they had broken the spirit 
    of those who had lived in that far off realm, KAAOS and a lesser faction began 
    to struggle for control. </font></p>
  <p><font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="-1">The one faction wished 
    to move on, to continue the way of bloodshed and domination against new peoples 
    instead of staying among the spineless. The other faction wished to stay in 
    the same realm where the people lay cowering already. The forces of KAAOS, 
    having made their decision, left the realm of the weak and moved on to new 
    lands where a challenge existed. The leader, one named Malhavok, had brought 
    the most evil and most vile lot with him, leaving the other faction and its 
    weaker members to go their own way. </font></p>
  <p><font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="-1">Thus, KAAOS was born 
    anew, as the movement ended up in the elders cleaning house and weeding out 
    of the weaker members who didnt have the heart. The other faction, chuckled 
    the father as he spoke to his son, became a ragtag band of the slow of wit 
    and weak of soul, who some have heard of as The Mercs. They always strived 
    their hardest to be like their rival guild KAAOS, but they lacked the strength 
    or the wit to survive such a task, and thus they sank into near anonimity. 
    </font></p>
  <p><font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="-1">His father continued 
    to tell the story, his smile gone from his lips now. While the mercs were 
    always stuck in their own private cesspool of mediocrity, KAAOS flourished. 
    Whereever they went, rivers of blood flowed under their feet. Those who stood 
    before them were crushed and broken, there souls damned to eternal torment 
    at the hands of these Gods of KAAOS. </font></p>
  <p><font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="-1">Then that fateful day 
    came, when the realm that they had conquered was thrown so far into anarchy 
    and chaos, that all of the people were either slain or forced to flee. Thus, 
    that realm ceased to exist and KAAOS was forced to find a new home. A tear 
    began to fall from the corner of the father's eye as he talked to his son. 
    </font></p>
  <p><font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="-1">"My son," he said, "KAAOS 
    has come here. None of these lands are safe. Even Lord British and his followers 
    are no match for them. We now enter into a dark time.. a time of pain. A time 
    of fear. A time of death." The old man was suddenly awoken from his flashback 
    as a child shook his hand violently. The old man tried to speak, tried to 
    form a reply, but all he could do was gasp for breath and clutch his chest. 
    As he fought against the clawing hand of death, his body began to shake in 
    fear as visions of these dark clad Gods of KAAOS shot through his head.</font></p>
  <p><font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="-1"> Then abruptly, he fell 
    backwards, sprawled on his back ontop of the rock which he had once sat upon. 
    The book fell to the ground with a dull thud and at that instant lightning 
    flashed across the sky and the storm came. Rain and hail began to pummel the 
    earth, causing the children to flee back to their homes, but no child would 
    ever be the same. No child could ever be the same after listening to the story 
    of the old man and after seeing the utter look of terror and anguish that 
    was written upon his face as his life and soul were taken from his body. </font></p>
  <p><font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="-1">Even as the children 
    were running from the storm's destructive power, a new sound could be heard 
    by those who listened. Amidst the thunder and confusion, a low, amused laughter 
    could be heard.. and everyone who heard it knew where it was coming from. 
    As fear swept through the people, the Gods of KAAOS laughed. KAAOS had finally 
    arrived.</font></p>
  <p><font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="-1"><i> Kal Mirage - KAAOS 
    AGM </i></font></p>		</td>
	</tr>
